******
[3] Cholera - Malawi (Central Region)
Date: Fri 5 Feb 2016
Source: Zambia Daily Mail [edited]
https://www.daily-mail.co.zm/?p=58293


The government has issued an alert on a possible outbreak of cholera in Chipata [Eastern Province of Zambia] after the waterborne disease claimed 4 lives in Kasungu, a border district in neighbouring Malawi. Chipata district commissioner Kalungu Zulu told journalists in Chipata that Kasungu has recorded 20 cases of cholera and 4 deaths since the disease broke out early this week [week of 1 Feb 2016]. Mr Zulu is concerned that cholera could spread to Chipata due to its proximity with Kasungu.

"I am appealing to both traditional leaders and clergymen to sensitize people on how the disease can be prevented and for now, people should avoid public gatherings," Mr Zulu said. He said Malawian authorities confirmed the outbreak of cholera in Kasungu and that Chipata is on alert because the disease could reverse economic gains. He said the chances of the Malawian traders traveling to Chipata and their Zambians counterparts traveling to Kasungu are high and that it is important for residents to be forewarned.

Mr Zulu appealed to Chipata residents not to buy foodstuff from street vendors and that fruits like mangoes, which are sold in streets of Chipata, are brought in from Malawi. He directed Chipata Municipal Council to intensify inspection of markets and restaurants to ensure they operate in good sanitary conditions. Kasungu is a district in the Central Region of Malawi, borders Zambia and has a population of 480 659.

