******
Asia
[4] Diarrhea - India (Manipur State) poss. _E. coli_
Date: Wed 3 Feb 2016
Source: The Sangai Express [edited]
http://www.thesangaiexpress.com/mysterious-disease-at-lilong-e-coli-not-cholera-health-director/


The mysterious disease that broke out at Lilong area and led to the hospitalisation of about 200 people is not cholera but _E. coli_, which causes intestinal infection. Symptoms of intestinal infection include diarrhea, abdominal pain and fever. Necessary laboratory tests have confirmed this.

Speaking to The Sangai Express, Health Director Dr O Ibomcha said that laboratory test of the samples collected from the patients have confirmed that the disease is _E. coli_ and not cholera.

Stating that specialist doctors at Lilong PHC [Primary Health Centre] are closely monitoring the situation, Dr Ibomcha said that tests are also underway to see if there is any case of Arsenic poisoning. The result however will take some more time, he added.

On the other hand, the Health Director has urged the people of Manipur not to proceed or visit countries in Latin America, Central America, and the Caribbean countries to protect themselves from Zika virus.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[_E. coli_ can be isolated in large numbers from human stool. Such isolation does not imply that the organism is or is not the cause of diarrhea. More information is needed to say that the _E. coli_ is an enteropath related to a variety of mechanisms.

The following is derived from Lutwick LI: Enterohemorrhagic _E. coli_ infections. In: Confronting Emerging Zoonoses: The One Health Paradigm. Yamada A, Kahn LH, Kaplan B, Monath TP, Woodall J, Conti LA (eds) Springer, Tokyo, Japan, 2014, pp 77-112.

"_E. coli_ is by far the most common facultative (can grow both aerobically or anaerobically) Gram-negative bacillus in the human intestinal tract. Within its niche in the intestinal tract, the organism is part of the normal bacterial flora with many functions to help its human host including preventing pathogen colonization, degrading dietary and in situ-produced compounds and producing nutrients. Although the pathogenicity of these normal flora strains of the organism occurs when the commensal is allowed to enter sterile parts of the body including the peritoneum, urinary tract and blood stream, some _E. coli_ strains have acquired virulence factors to become enteropathogenic for man. There are currently 6 enteropaths of the bacterium described (enterotoxigenic, enteropathogenic, enteroinvasive, diffuse adhering, enteroaggregative, and enterohemorrhagic). The enterohemorrhagic _E. coli_ is the potentially the most dangerous and is the one which is zoonotic in origin (primarily from cattle) and the one generally just called _E. coli_ in the lay press." - Mod.LL

Manipur State in northeastern India can be seen on the maps at http://www.mapsofindia.com/maps/india/india-political-map.htm and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3997119,311. - Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ]
